article.description:
The Minnesota Lynx snapped an 18-game losing
streak to the Sparks with a 78-66 victory Friday night and secured a playoff berth in the process.
article.headline: Lynx beat Sparks for first time since '99
article.linkText: Lynx snap 18-game skid vs. Sparks, clinch playoffs
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The last time the Minnesota Lynx beat the Los
Angeles Sparks, rookies Nicole Ohlde and Vanessa Hayden were still
in high school.

Ohlde scored 19 points and Hayden added 16 and a season-high
nine rebounds Friday night to help the Lynx beat the Sparks 78-66
and clinch a playoff berth in the process.

The Lynx, who last beat Los Angeles on June 24, 1999, had lost
18 in a row to the Sparks.

"This is something we hoped we would see from the two of
them," Lynx coach Suzie McConnell Serio said. "They complement
each other very well.

"Ohlde has finesse and is a very versatile player, and we want
to get Vanessa the ball down low and try to dominate inside."

McConnell Serio said it was Hayden's 14 points in the second
half that "was a difference maker" in this game.

The Lynx, who improved to 18-15, tied the club's season record
for victories and secured a playoff spot when Phoenix lost to the
Washington Mystics 74-67.

"This is obviously a big win," McConnell Serio said. "We
talked about taking the pressure off, not feeling like we had to
win to make the playoffs. We came out relaxed and gained confidence
as the game went along."

The score was tied at 48 when Ohlde made two free throws with
12:54 to play.

Lisa Leslie committed a flagrant foul 40 seconds later and
Teresa Edwards converted both free throws. Hayden followed with a
hook shot to give the Lynx a 54-48 lead with 12:03 left.

Los Angeles (24-9) narrowed the deficit to 56-52 with 11:11
left, but Hayden scored six points during a 9-1 run that extended
Minnesota's lead to 65-53 with 9:33 remaining.

Tamika Whitmore scored a season-high 18 points for the Sparks,
who lost for just the second time at home this season.

Mwadi Mabika added 15 points, Christi Thomas had a career-high
11 rebounds and Nikki Teasley had 10 assists, tying a season best.

Leslie, who fouled out with 8:26 to play, finished with nine
points and seven rebounds.
